content:
**In today's world, modern applications rely heavily on APIs to handle data exchange between the frontend and backend.** A REST API (**Representational State Transfer**) is one of the most widely used ways to structure communication between client and server.

In this blog, we'll build a **simple REST API** using **Node.js** and **Express.js**.

---

**🛠️ Prerequisites:**
- Basic knowledge of **JavaScript**
- **Node.js** and **npm** installed
- Understanding of **REST API concepts**

---

**Step 1 — Initialize the Project**

Create a new project folder and initialize it:

```bash
mkdir rest-api-node && cd rest-api-node
npm init -y
```

---

**Step 2 — Install Dependencies**

We'll use **Express.js** to handle routing and API endpoints:

```bash
npm install express
```

---

**Step 3 — Create the Server**

Create an **index.js** file and set up the basic Express server:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const PORT = 3000;

app.use(express.json());

app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

---

**Step 4 — Build API Routes**

We'll create **RESTful API endpoints** to perform **CRUD operations**:

```javascript
let users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'John Doe' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Jane Smith' }
];

// Get all users
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
    res.json(users);
});

// Get user by ID
app.get('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
    const user = users.find(u => u.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
    if (!user) return res.status(404).send('User not found');
    res.json(user);
});

// Add a new user
app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
    const newUser = { id: users.length + 1, name: req.body.name };
    users.push(newUser);
    res.status(201).json(newUser);
});

// Update user by ID
app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
    const user = users.find(u => u.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
    if (!user) return res.status(404).send('User not found');
    user.name = req.body.name;
    res.json(user);
});

// Delete user by ID
app.delete('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
    users = users.filter(u => u.id !== parseInt(req.params.id));
    res.status(204).send();
});
```

---

**Step 5 — Test the API**

Use **Postman** or your **browser** to test the endpoints:

- **GET** `/users` → Fetch all users
- **GET** `/users/1` → Fetch a single user
- **POST** `/users` → Add a new user
- **PUT** `/users/1` → Update a user
- **DELETE** `/users/1` → Delete a user

---

**🎯 Conclusion**

You've successfully built a **basic REST API** using **Node.js** and **Express.js**. You can now **enhance** it by:
- Connecting to a **database** like MongoDB
- Adding **authentication & authorization**
- Deploying it to **cloud platforms** like Vercel, Render, or AWS.

**In modern web development, Next.js has become one of the most popular frameworks for building full-stack applications.** It allows developers to create both **frontend UI** and **backend APIs** in a single project. When combined with **Tailwind CSS**, it enables you to build beautiful, responsive, and scalable applications quickly.

In this blog, we'll create a **REST API** inside a **Next.js** app and style the frontend using **Tailwind CSS**.

---

**🛠️ Prerequisites:**
- Basic knowledge of **JavaScript** and **React**
- Familiarity with **Next.js**
- **Node.js** and **npm** installed

---

**Step 1 — Create a New Next.js Project**

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest rest-api-next
cd rest-api-next
```

During setup, select **JavaScript** and enable **Tailwind CSS** if prompted.

---

**Step 2 — Install Tailwind CSS (if not added during setup)**

```bash
npm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer
npx tailwindcss init -p
```

Configure **tailwind.config.js**:

```javascript
module.exports = {
  content: ["./pages/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx}", "./components/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx}"],
  theme: {
    extend: {},
  },
  plugins: [],
}
```

Add Tailwind directives to **styles/globals.css**:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

---

**Step 3 — Create API Routes in Next.js**

Next.js allows you to build **REST APIs** inside the `pages/api` folder. Create a file:

`pages/api/users.js`

```javascript
let users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'John Doe' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Jane Smith' }
];

export default function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === 'GET') {
    res.status(200).json(users);
  } 
  else if (req.method === 'POST') {
    const newUser = { id: users.length + 1, name: req.body.name };
    users.push(newUser);
    res.status(201).json(newUser);
  } 
  else if (req.method === 'PUT') {
    const { id, name } = req.body;
    users = users.map(u => u.id === id ? { ...u, name } : u);
    res.status(200).json({ message: 'User updated', users });
  } 
  else if (req.method === 'DELETE') {
    const { id } = req.body;
    users = users.filter(u => u.id !== id);
    res.status(204).end();
  } 
  else {
    res.status(405).json({ message: 'Method not allowed' });
  }
}
```

---

**Step 4 — Build a Simple Frontend with Tailwind CSS**

Edit **pages/index.js** to fetch and display users:

```javascript
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export default function Home() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/api/users')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setUsers(data));
  }, []);

  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen bg-gray-100 flex flex-col items-center p-8">
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-600 mb-6">User List</h1>
      <div className="bg-white shadow-lg rounded-2xl p-6 w-full max-w-md">
        {users.map(user => (
          <p key={user.id} className="text-lg text-gray-700">• {user.name}</p>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

**Step 5 — Test Your API**

Use **Postman**, **Thunder Client**, or the browser to test:

- **GET** `/api/users` → Fetch all users
- **POST** `/api/users` → Add a new user
- **PUT** `/api/users` → Update an existing user
- **DELETE** `/api/users` → Delete a user

---

**🎯 Conclusion**

You've successfully built a **REST API** using **Next.js** and styled the frontend using **Tailwind CSS**. This approach allows you to create **full-stack applications** without managing separate frontend and backend repositories. You can now enhance the project by:
- Connecting to a real **database** like **MongoDB** or **PostgreSQL**
- Adding **JWT authentication**
- Deploying the app on **Vercel** for free hosting.

**React Hooks** are one of the most powerful features introduced in **React 16.8**. They allow developers to use **state** and **lifecycle methods** inside **functional components**, making code simpler, cleaner, and more reusable.

In this guide, we'll explore all the **essential React Hooks** with examples and best practices.

---

**📌 What Are React Hooks?**
React Hooks are special functions that let you **hook into React features** like **state**, **context**, and **lifecycle methods** without writing class components.

**Why Use Hooks?**
- Simplify your code by removing class components
- Improve code reusability
- Better performance and maintainability

---

**🛠️ Commonly Used React Hooks**

### **1. useState — Manage Component State**
The **useState** hook lets you add state to functional components.

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Count: {count}</h1>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**How it works:**
- `useState(0)` → Initializes state with **0**
- `setCount()` → Updates the state

---

### **2. useEffect — Handle Side Effects**
The **useEffect** hook lets you perform **side effects** like **API calls**, **event listeners**, or **updating the DOM**.

```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function UserData() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setUsers(data));
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Users</h2>
      <ul>
        {users.map(user => <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>)}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Key Points:**
- `useEffect(() => {...}, [])` → Runs only once when the component mounts
- Remove the `[]` to make it run on **every render**

---

### **3. useContext — Manage Global State**
The **useContext** hook allows components to access **global data** without **prop drilling**.

```javascript
import React, { createContext, useContext } from 'react';

const ThemeContext = createContext('light');

function ThemedButton() {
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  return <button style={{ background: theme === 'dark' ? '#333' : '#fff' }}>Click Me</button>;
}

function App() {
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value="dark">
      <ThemedButton />
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}
```

---

### **4. useReducer — Manage Complex State**
The **useReducer** hook is useful when state logic becomes complex.

```javascript
import React, { useReducer } from 'react';

const reducer = (state, action) => {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'INCREMENT':
      return { count: state.count + 1 };
    case 'DECREMENT':
      return { count: state.count - 1 };
    default:
      return state;
  }
};

function Counter() {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, { count: 0 });

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{state.count}</h1>
      <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'INCREMENT' })}>+</button>
      <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'DECREMENT' })}>-</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

### **5. Custom Hooks — Reuse Logic**
Custom hooks let you **extract reusable logic** from components.

```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function useWindowWidth() {
  const [width, setWidth] = useState(window.innerWidth);

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleResize = () => setWidth(window.innerWidth);
    window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

    return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  }, []);

  return width;
}

function App() {
  const width = useWindowWidth();
  return <h1>Window width: {width}px</h1>;
}
```

---

**⚡ Best Practices for React Hooks**
- Always use hooks **at the top level**
- Avoid using hooks inside loops or conditions
- Use **custom hooks** for repetitive logic
- Combine hooks smartly for better performance

---

**🎯 Conclusion**
React Hooks make **functional components** much more powerful and cleaner. By mastering **useState**, **useEffect**, **useContext**, **useReducer**, and **custom hooks**, you can write **scalable and reusable code**. They are now the **standard way** of writing modern React applications.
